1
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:37,562
Despite all the warnings,
she was smoking in bed, fell asleep.

2
00:02:37,905 --> 00:02:39,316
Bad move.

3
00:02:47,581 --> 00:02:49,739
And the fire begins.

4
00:02:58,592 --> 00:03:00,252
It's showtime.

5
00:03:04,013 --> 00:03:06,683
Don't worry, ma'am! I'm here to save you!

6
00:03:10,979 --> 00:03:13,730
Keep those people back!
This is an emergency!

7
00:03:14,690 --> 00:03:17,360
Don't you dare die on me!

8
00:03:18,611 --> 00:03:20,769
Breathe, damn it, breathe!

9
00:03:23,908 --> 00:03:25,616
She's going to make it!

10
00:03:32,707 --> 00:03:33,787
What the...?

11
00:04:18,752 --> 00:04:20,247
Damn!

12
00:04:50,033 --> 00:04:54,030
Though it may be hard to believe
a single biology professor...

13
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:58,581
...making in excess of $17,500 a year
could find time...

14
00:04:58,666 --> 00:05:02,165
...to grade your first biology
research papers, l did.

15
00:05:02,336 --> 00:05:06,001
As you can see,
there was a shocking statistical anomaly:

16
00:05:06,214 --> 00:05:08,254
Pretty much all of you got A's.

17
00:05:12,846 --> 00:05:17,010
congratulate yourselves.
l have a good feeling about this group.

18
00:05:17,268 --> 00:05:22,262
And l think the parade of A's
will continue to the end of the semester.

19
00:05:22,523 --> 00:05:24,515
So much for the bell curve.

20
00:05:24,858 --> 00:05:26,268
Bell curves suck!

21
00:05:27,694 --> 00:05:29,188
-Mr. Kane?
-Dr. Kane?

22
00:05:29,529 --> 00:05:32,102
There seems to be a mistake here.

23
00:05:32,866 --> 00:05:35,701
My brother and l each got a c-.

24
00:05:35,952 --> 00:05:37,695
c-. Me, too.

25
00:05:38,704 --> 00:05:41,872
Allow me to share something
with the entire class.

26
00:05:42,208 --> 00:05:47,036
As l was grading papers, l came across
two gems, both entitled ''cells are Bad.''

27
00:05:48,214 --> 00:05:52,674
Both with just one paragraph, which
l unfortunately committed to memory.

28
00:05:53,010 --> 00:05:54,718
''cells are Bad.

29
00:05:55,054 --> 00:05:56,845
''My uncle lives in a cell.

30
00:05:57,055 --> 00:06:01,552
''lt's 10 by 12 and he has to read
the same boring magazine every day.

31
00:06:02,561 --> 00:06:04,139
''The end.''

32
00:06:07,233 --> 00:06:10,566
You're talking about our papers,
aren't you, Dr. Kane?

33
00:06:10,694 --> 00:06:11,892
Yes, l am.

34
00:06:11,987 --> 00:06:15,402
And although my standards
are nowhere near where they used to be...

35
00:06:15,490 --> 00:06:20,069
...l couldn't put an A on those beauties.
l hope you understand.

36
00:06:21,245 --> 00:06:23,997
-Sure.
-Yeah, okay.

37
00:06:24,249 --> 00:06:28,246
Okay, let's get back to work
at the periodic table, which....

38
00:06:29,087 --> 00:06:31,079
A meteor? Where?

39
00:06:33,257 --> 00:06:37,172
Route 89A. Yeah, l got it.

40
00:06:39,431 --> 00:06:42,929
Rest assured, l will be there. Okay, 'bye.

41
00:06:48,105 --> 00:06:50,014
How does it look, Professor?

42
00:06:51,609 --> 00:06:53,019
It's tight.

43
00:06:53,777 --> 00:06:56,351
Really, really tight, Nadine.

44
00:06:56,447 --> 00:07:00,278
But not too tight.
You just don't have the points. Sorry.

45
00:07:00,617 --> 00:07:03,618
Don't take it too hard.
Geology's tougher than people think.

46
00:07:03,954 --> 00:07:06,279
Are you sure? could you check again?

47
00:07:06,456 --> 00:07:09,208
l need this credit
to get into nursing school.

48
00:07:11,294 --> 00:07:12,574
Nursing school?

49
00:07:13,630 --> 00:07:15,919
Wouldn't you prefer a different profession?

50
00:07:16,007 --> 00:07:18,580
One where lives
were not dependent on you?

51
00:07:20,595 --> 00:07:24,094
Actually, what l want to be
is Miss Arizona.

52
00:07:24,307 --> 00:07:28,636
But my pageant consultant says
nursing school will impress the judges.

53
00:07:28,895 --> 00:07:30,970
They'll think l want to help people--

54
00:07:31,063 --> 00:07:32,558
Ready for lunch?

55
00:07:34,609 --> 00:07:36,766
Or have you already eaten?

56
00:07:38,195 --> 00:07:41,861
I'm just concluding
a teacher-student conference with Nadine.

57
00:07:41,990 --> 00:07:46,818
Harry, your dedication to your job
is an inspiration to us all.

58
00:07:48,538 --> 00:07:52,323
Regrettably, l have a prior lunch
engagement with Professor Kane.

59
00:07:52,668 --> 00:07:56,332
We'll discuss your extra credit later.
cheer up.

60
00:07:58,507 --> 00:08:00,085
Let me grab my stuff.

61
00:08:06,014 --> 00:08:07,591
Where are you taking me?

62
00:08:07,682 --> 00:08:10,849
-A meteor hit last night.
-That's what that was.

63
00:08:11,853 --> 00:08:15,268
As Glen canyon's representative
for the U.S. Geological Survey...

64
00:08:15,356 --> 00:08:17,313
...l have to check it out.

65
00:08:17,400 --> 00:08:20,353
I'm taking you in case
l have to do something scientific.

66
00:08:20,444 --> 00:08:21,440
Then we eat.

67
00:08:21,529 --> 00:08:23,937
You're with the USGS?

68
00:08:24,198 --> 00:08:26,190
l signed up over the Internet.

69
00:08:27,201 --> 00:08:31,828
Or were you on a cheerleader site and
accidentally got linked to the USGS site?

70
00:08:32,539 --> 00:08:34,033
Something like that.

71
00:08:35,209 --> 00:08:36,158
Watch it. Take it easy.

72
00:08:36,252 --> 00:08:39,205
That's my baby. Take it easy.

73
00:08:41,215 --> 00:08:43,373
come on! Be careful!

74
00:08:43,717 --> 00:08:46,718
Who's going to pay for the damage
to my goddamn car?

75
00:08:47,053 --> 00:08:50,055
l told you, we don't do that.
It.'s force majeure.

76
00:08:50,307 --> 00:08:54,221
Force majeure, my ass!
That car's a classic '73 Buick Riv.

77
00:08:56,605 --> 00:08:57,802
Who are you?

78
00:08:58,064 --> 00:09:01,231
Harry Block,
United States Geological Survey.

79
00:09:01,484 --> 00:09:05,184
My secretary, Ira Kane.
We're here to investigate the meteor...

80
00:09:05,279 --> 00:09:07,106
...if that is what it is.

81
00:09:07,407 --> 00:09:09,979
Of course it is. It almost blew up my car.

82
00:09:10,409 --> 00:09:13,079
I'm still fuzzy
on why you were here at night.

83
00:09:13,413 --> 00:09:14,955
With Betty Lou here.

84
00:09:15,248 --> 00:09:20,242
l was practicing for my fireman's exam,
which started seven minutes ago.

85
00:09:20,419 --> 00:09:23,170
So I'd appreciate it if you'd let me go.

86
00:09:23,505 --> 00:09:25,997
So you and the blonde found the meteor?

87
00:09:26,342 --> 00:09:30,339
Yeah, l found it.
It bounced my car 200 feet in the air.

88
00:09:30,679 --> 00:09:33,846
-can l go?
-Bob, get him out of here.

89
00:09:37,519 --> 00:09:38,930
Don't leave town.

90
00:09:40,688 --> 00:09:44,022
Well, Sheriff, is this the...

91
00:09:45,026 --> 00:09:47,018
...point of penetration?

92
00:09:47,361 --> 00:09:51,194
Yeah. It punched through into a cavern
about 80 feet down.

93
00:09:54,452 --> 00:09:55,448
Now that's a hole!

94
00:09:59,582 --> 00:10:00,993
Damn it!

95
00:10:01,542 --> 00:10:03,286
Next time, you carry the case.

96
00:10:03,377 --> 00:10:08,004
You're the USGS representative.
That responsibility comes with the badge.

97
00:10:08,174 --> 00:10:10,843
Oh, my God. Look at that.

98
00:10:12,678 --> 00:10:15,347
l believe we've located the target.

99
00:10:15,723 --> 00:10:17,431
Two big smiles, fellas.

100
00:10:17,558 --> 00:10:19,550
cheese!

101
00:10:19,726 --> 00:10:22,052
Okay, hold it up now.

102
00:10:24,230 --> 00:10:26,389
-Got it.
-It's really hot.

103
00:10:26,733 --> 00:10:28,393
I'll hold you up.

104
00:10:29,445 --> 00:10:31,401
Show a little more nightstick.

105
00:10:31,488 --> 00:10:33,148
Look at these jackasses.

106
00:10:33,406 --> 00:10:37,190
Muscle pose. Give me big smiles!
Looking good.

107
00:10:37,410 --> 00:10:40,910
At ease, gentlemen! The feds are here.

108
00:10:41,414 --> 00:10:43,406
Feds? What feds?

109
00:10:43,749 --> 00:10:45,244
Who let you down here?

110
00:10:45,334 --> 00:10:46,995
Let's not get combative.

111
00:10:47,504 --> 00:10:51,501
The USGS and local law enforcement
have a long history of cooperation.

112
00:10:51,757 --> 00:10:55,341
We're just here to get
some scientific samples. If that's okay.

113
00:10:56,261 --> 00:11:01,257
Yeah, sure. We got
all the photographic evidence we need.

114
00:11:02,017 --> 00:11:04,591
-carry on.
-Thanks. Keep up the good work.

115
00:11:08,565 --> 00:11:09,846
Wow.

116
00:11:20,077 --> 00:11:24,026
It just hit last night
and it has stuff growing on it.

117
00:11:26,291 --> 00:11:27,619
could be cave moss.

118
00:11:27,709 --> 00:11:30,461
After just a few hours? That's peculiar.

119
00:11:30,795 --> 00:11:33,286
Let's get a sample and get out of here.

120
00:11:44,434 --> 00:11:46,093
It's bleeding.

121
00:11:46,936 --> 00:11:49,427
It's a rock that bleeds.

122
00:11:51,107 --> 00:11:54,440
Now that's really peculiar.

123
00:11:55,528 --> 00:11:56,939
Let's bag it.

124
00:12:07,122 --> 00:12:10,787
l don't know if this USGS gig
is all it's cracked up to be.

125
00:12:11,626 --> 00:12:15,874
l mean, it pads out my résumé,
but am l growing as a person?

126
00:12:16,215 --> 00:12:19,749
Am l growing as a Division 3
women's volleyball coach?

127
00:12:23,137 --> 00:12:25,711
You going to do that spectro-thingy test?

128
00:12:25,890 --> 00:12:29,508
Spectrograph.
Yeah, l will do a spectroscopic analysis.

129
00:12:29,602 --> 00:12:31,262
Your résumé will shine.

130
00:12:31,896 --> 00:12:34,933
l got to get to the game.
Let me know if you find anything.

131
00:12:40,154 --> 00:12:43,523
Ira, are you sure you can handle this
by your lonesome?

132
00:12:45,618 --> 00:12:46,816
All right.

133
00:13:23,863 --> 00:13:25,357
That's impossible.

134
00:14:05,028 --> 00:14:06,855
Ten base pairs.

135
00:14:10,700 --> 00:14:11,814
That can't be.

136
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:18,749
come on, ladies! Look alive up here!

137
00:14:24,922 --> 00:14:29,085
Tina! When Lisa goes for the spike,
you have to cover the line!

138
00:14:29,343 --> 00:14:32,379
Lisa! Two hands, okay? Two hands!

139
00:14:32,721 --> 00:14:34,963
God gave you two hands for a reason!

140
00:14:35,098 --> 00:14:37,091
Big news. The most amazing thing.

141
00:14:37,768 --> 00:14:40,685
The meteor samples are teeming
with one-celled organisms.

142
00:14:40,770 --> 00:14:42,893
Their metabolic rates are off the charts.

143
00:14:42,981 --> 00:14:45,982
They're dividing at an incredible rate.
Almost exponential.

144
00:14:46,693 --> 00:14:49,018
Their DNA has ten base pairs.

145
00:14:49,613 --> 00:14:51,938
Ten base pairs. That's good to know.

146
00:14:52,074 --> 00:14:55,240
Harry, the DNA of all earth life
has only four base pairs.

147
00:14:56,119 --> 00:14:58,953
come on, ladies! Look alive!

148
00:15:00,456 --> 00:15:01,619
Harry...

149
00:15:02,458 --> 00:15:05,459
...these are organisms from another world.

150
00:15:06,629 --> 00:15:08,289
They're aliens.

151
00:15:11,675 --> 00:15:15,341
Is the Nobel Prize paid in instalments
or a lump sum, like the lottery?

152
00:15:15,471 --> 00:15:17,796
Let's not get ahead of ourselves.

153
00:15:18,140 --> 00:15:22,470
I'm not. I'm concerned about
the potential tax consequences.

154
00:15:27,024 --> 00:15:29,859
-Why in here?
-l just want to be cautious.

155
00:15:34,114 --> 00:15:35,608
Our discovery.

156
00:15:36,449 --> 00:15:37,943
I'm all tingly.

157
00:15:41,955 --> 00:15:43,069
Wow.

158
00:15:46,793 --> 00:15:51,004
I'm no biologist, but how many cells
do single-celled organisms have?

159
00:15:52,632 --> 00:15:56,463
If we want to be big important scientists,
you have to act the part.

160
00:15:57,303 --> 00:15:58,963
Take a look.

161
00:16:14,778 --> 00:16:17,186
There are multi-cellular organisms in there.

162
00:16:18,782 --> 00:16:19,981
l know.

163
00:16:20,074 --> 00:16:22,566
-They weren't there before.
-They snuck in.

164
00:16:22,661 --> 00:16:24,819
No, there was no sneaking in.

165
00:16:26,581 --> 00:16:28,621
It's too amazing.

166
00:16:31,169 --> 00:16:32,995
It's like they're evolving.

167
00:16:33,337 --> 00:16:34,713
They're growing.

168
00:16:35,089 --> 00:16:37,296
Growing into more complex organisms.

169
00:16:39,009 --> 00:16:40,290
It's evolution.

170
00:16:42,013 --> 00:16:43,970
Nobel, here we come.

171
00:16:46,016 --> 00:16:49,468
But it's 200 million years worth
in just a few hours.

172
00:16:52,606 --> 00:16:53,804
That's fast.

173
00:16:55,526 --> 00:16:57,518
You have no idea.

174
00:16:59,363 --> 00:17:00,857
Get ready!

175
00:17:00,990 --> 00:17:03,659
On my signal! Go!

176
00:17:06,203 --> 00:17:08,030
Recruit, wake up.

177
00:17:08,580 --> 00:17:10,240
Wake up!

178
00:17:10,582 --> 00:17:12,575
Go!

179
00:17:13,710 --> 00:17:17,079
-The hose! This thing here!
-Sorry.

180
00:17:18,715 --> 00:17:20,126
Move it!

181
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:22,921
Wayne, go! come on!

182
00:17:29,725 --> 00:17:31,884
These things happen, buddy.

183
00:17:33,229 --> 00:17:35,387
There's another test in six months.

184
00:17:35,731 --> 00:17:38,898
Six months? l can't wait six months!

185
00:17:39,402 --> 00:17:42,319
At least you have the pool gig
at the country club.

186
00:17:42,404 --> 00:17:43,982
Great. Thanks a lot.

187
00:17:45,241 --> 00:17:46,486
Drive careful.

188
00:17:48,285 --> 00:17:51,120
l got it. l do this.

189
00:17:58,837 --> 00:18:00,995
Looks like we have visitors.

190
00:18:08,930 --> 00:18:13,924
class, since this is our first field trip,
l want you to obey some simple rules.

191
00:18:14,435 --> 00:18:15,598
Dirt.

192
00:18:15,937 --> 00:18:17,266
Nice footwear.

193
00:18:17,522 --> 00:18:20,143
Perfect for spelunking.
Now don't touch anything.

194
00:18:20,233 --> 00:18:22,985
Don't move anything.
Don't even breathe unless we say.

195
00:18:23,069 --> 00:18:25,026
Wear your protective gloves at all times.

196
00:18:25,112 --> 00:18:26,606
Why do we have to do this?

197
00:18:26,697 --> 00:18:30,530
Field experience.
The meat and potatoes of geology.

198
00:18:30,618 --> 00:18:32,859
-Will this be on the final?
-Yes.

199
00:18:32,953 --> 00:18:35,445
-Officer, nice to see you.
-What's up, Professor?

200
00:18:35,540 --> 00:18:37,200
We came to pick up the rock.

201
00:18:37,291 --> 00:18:39,283
Pick it up? What?

202
00:18:40,419 --> 00:18:44,547
Orders from the USGS.
They want it under controlled conditions.

203
00:18:44,631 --> 00:18:46,173
It's very technical.

204
00:18:46,967 --> 00:18:49,293
Oh, technical stuff. It's technical.

205
00:18:49,470 --> 00:18:51,129
Okay. Go right ahead.

206
00:18:51,221 --> 00:18:53,463
-We'll just haul it right out.
-Sure.

207
00:18:53,640 --> 00:18:56,309
Deke and Danny?
Remember what we talked about?

208
00:18:56,559 --> 00:18:59,976
You're in charge of hoisting.
Get the winch to the hole.

209
00:19:00,313 --> 00:19:04,180
Fellas? Stop nodding, and stare at me
for a second, okay?

210
00:19:05,193 --> 00:19:06,356
Focus.

211
00:19:07,320 --> 00:19:10,486
-You understand what l want you to do?
-Yeah.

212
00:19:10,823 --> 00:19:11,986
Go do it.

213
00:19:22,668 --> 00:19:26,417
Ira, I'm picking up
a heavy creepy vibe here.

214
00:19:27,006 --> 00:19:28,998
Yeah, a lot has changed.

215
00:19:32,053 --> 00:19:36,513
class, l know these look like mushrooms,
but refrain from eating them.

216
00:19:40,852 --> 00:19:42,395
It smells disgusting.

217
00:19:43,105 --> 00:19:45,477
Nadine, sometimes science stinks.

218
00:19:46,691 --> 00:19:48,601
It's the game we play, baby.

219
00:19:52,822 --> 00:19:56,274
Rotten egg smell. Hydrogen sulfide, right?

220
00:19:56,493 --> 00:19:59,778
With ammonia and methane.
It's converting the atmosphere.

221
00:19:59,871 --> 00:20:02,742
Look at all this rudimentary plant life.
It's amazing.

222
00:20:05,459 --> 00:20:09,956
Not to get all girly here, but l feel
something wiggling around my toes.

223
00:20:15,470 --> 00:20:17,545
The ground does seem to be moving.

224
00:20:29,066 --> 00:20:30,145
Flatworms.

225
00:20:30,442 --> 00:20:31,853
Millions of them!

226
00:20:32,736 --> 00:20:33,650
Yuck!

227
00:20:37,907 --> 00:20:40,613
Barely 18 hours
and we already have flatworms.

228
00:20:41,245 --> 00:20:42,868
-Look.
-There they are!

229
00:20:42,996 --> 00:20:44,656
Hi, Dr. Kane!

230
00:20:47,709 --> 00:20:49,867
-l almost went down on that one!
-Awesome.

231
00:20:53,590 --> 00:20:55,297
come here, little buddy.

232
00:20:59,554 --> 00:21:00,964
l won't hurt you.

233
00:21:08,187 --> 00:21:10,263
You didn't hurt it. You killed it.

234
00:21:10,356 --> 00:21:12,396
The oxygen must have killed it.

235
00:21:12,984 --> 00:21:15,225
It must need its own atmosphere to live.

236
00:21:16,945 --> 00:21:20,812
Grab a specimen jar. We'll scoop
some atmosphere in there with them.

237
00:21:23,619 --> 00:21:27,236
It took us two billion years to do
what they did in a couple of days.

238
00:21:28,623 --> 00:21:31,708
Those germs are the embodiment
of the American dream.

239
00:21:33,044 --> 00:21:35,796
I'm sorry to interrupt, Professor Block.

240
00:21:35,964 --> 00:21:39,546
But l was wondering if I'm correct
in assuming that that field trip...

241
00:21:39,634 --> 00:21:42,125
...fulfilled any of my missing
credit assignments?

242
00:21:42,637 --> 00:21:44,547
Nadine, you are a very...

243
00:21:44,638 --> 00:21:47,889
...very smart girl. If you would just focus.

244
00:21:53,064 --> 00:21:56,350
Professor, the little wiggly worm things
are breaking.

245
00:21:57,818 --> 00:21:59,146
Ira, look.

246
00:22:03,991 --> 00:22:06,197
It's not breaking. It's splitting.

247
00:22:06,660 --> 00:22:09,198
It's mitosis. That's how they reproduce.

248
00:22:09,996 --> 00:22:11,407
No sex?

249
00:22:11,999 --> 00:22:13,374
No time for sex.

250
00:22:14,418 --> 00:22:15,497
Bummer.

251
00:22:17,003 --> 00:22:19,495
-They're splitting again.
-Put it away.

252
00:22:20,173 --> 00:22:23,209
We call no one, we tell no one.
This is our secret.

253
